'''Haru Matsuri''' (春祭)<ref name="Daijisen">『{{ill|Daijisen|ja|大辞泉|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Daijisen|qq=}}』</ref><ref>Heibonsha 『{{ill|MyPedia|ja|マイペディア|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/MyPedia|qq=}}』</ref><ref>Heibonsha 『{{ill|Sekai Daihyakka Jiten|ja|世界大百科事典|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sekai Daihyakka Jiten|qq=}}』, 2nd Edition</ref><ref>Shogakukan 『{{ill|Nipponica|ja|日本大百科全書|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nipponica|qq=}}』</ref>, also called '''Spring Festival''' or '''Haru no Matsuri''' (はるまつり), is a general term for {{ill|festivals|ja|祭|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/festivals|qq=}} held in the {{ill|spring|ja|春|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/spring|qq=}}.

== Seasonal Word ==
As a {{ill|kigo|ja|季語|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/kigo|qq=}}, the term '''Haru Matsuri''' (春祭り) represents a seasonal word for spring (either for {{ill|early spring|ja|初春|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/early spring|qq=}} or the three months of spring, depending on the {{ill|saijiki|ja|歳時記|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/saijiki|qq=}}).<ref name="Kigosai">{{Cite web|和書|date=2011-02-16 |url=http://kigosai.sub.jp/kigo500e/341.html |title=春祭 |work=Kigosai Saijiki |publisher=Kigosai Saijiki Association |accessdate=2018-02-17}}</ref> It falls under the classification of {{ill|events|ja|行事|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/events|qq=}} or human affairs.<ref>"Events" and "human affairs" refer here to activities performed by humans.</ref> In terms of seasonal words, it encompasses festivals held during the spring season.<ref name="Kigosai" />
{{quotation|
* Example: The '''Haru Matsuri''' begins with the sprouting of old mulberries – {{ill|Shūson Mizuhara|ja|水原秋桜子|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shūson Mizuhara|qq=}}<ref name="Daijisen" />
* Example: '''Haru Matsuri''' beneath the mountains, few fresh monpe in sight – {{ill|Hakyō Ishida|ja|石田波郷|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hakyō Ishida|qq=}}
* Example: Valleys open to the sight of Norikura at '''Haru Matsuri''' – {{ill|Fura Maeda|ja|前田普羅|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fura Maeda|qq=}} 『Hida Tsumugi』 (published 1947)<ref name="Kigosai" />
* Example: Shellfish alive in a tank at '''Haru Matsuri''' – Yaehiro Hiroe 『Chikuma Literary Anthology』<ref name="Kigosai" />
}}
There are no sub-seasonal words for it. While no directly related seasonal words are listed, many spring festivals, such as the {{ill|Kinensai|ja|祈年祭|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kinensai|qq=}}, are seasonal words, which naturally relate to Haru Matsuri.

