'''Haru Matsuri''' (春祭)<ref name="Daijisen">『[[:en:Daijisen|Daijisen]]』</ref><ref>Heibonsha 『{{ill|MyPedia|ja|マイペディア|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/MyPedia|qq=|1=My Pedia|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11339782}}』</ref><ref>Heibonsha 『[[:en:Heibonsha World Encyclopedia|Sekai Daihyakka Jiten]]』, 2nd Edition</ref><ref>Shogakukan 『[[:en:Encyclopedia Nipponica|Nipponica]]』</ref>, also called '''Spring Festival''' or '''Haru no Matsuri''' (はるまつり), is a general term for [[:en:Festival|festivals]] held in the [[:en:Spring (season)|spring]].
== Seasonal Word == As a [[:en:Kigo|kigo]], the term '''Haru Matsuri''' (春祭り) represents a seasonal word for spring (either for {{ill|early spring|ja|初春|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/early spring|qq=|1=Hatsuharu|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q16870571}} or the three months of spring, depending on the [[:en:Saijiki|saijiki]]).<ref name="Kigosai">{{Cite web|和書|date=2011-02-16 |url=http://kigosai.sub.jp/kigo500e/341.html |title=春祭 |work=Kigosai Saijiki |publisher=Kigosai Saijiki Association |accessdate=2018-02-17}}</ref> It falls under the classification of {{ill|events|ja|行事|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/events|qq=|1=events|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11625998}} or human affairs.<ref>"Events" and "human affairs" refer here to activities performed by humans.</ref> In terms of seasonal words, it encompasses festivals held during the spring season.<ref name="Kigosai" /> {{quotation| * Example: The '''Haru Matsuri''' begins with the sprouting of old mulberries – [[:en:Shūōshi Mizuhara|Shūson Mizuhara]]<ref name="Daijisen" /> * Example: '''Haru Matsuri''' beneath the mountains, few fresh monpe in sight – [[:en:Ishida Hakyō|Hakyō Ishida]] * Example: Valleys open to the sight of Norikura at '''Haru Matsuri''' – {{ill|Fura Maeda|ja|前田普羅|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fura Maeda|qq=|1=Fura Maeda|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11397594}} 『Hida Tsumugi』 (published 1947)<ref name="Kigosai" /> * Example: Shellfish alive in a tank at '''Haru Matsuri''' – Yaehiro Hiroe 『Chikuma Literary Anthology』<ref name="Kigosai" /> }} There are no sub-seasonal words for it. While no directly related seasonal words are listed, many spring festivals, such as the [[:en:Kinen-sai|Kinensai]], are seasonal words, which naturally relate to Haru Matsuri.
